Studi is an award-winning actor, musician, and artist. But even before his notable performances in films such as “Dances with Wolves” (1990), “The Last of the Mohicans” (1992), and “Geronimo: An American Legend” (1993), Studi filled other important roles outside the film industry. He served in the U.S. Army during the Vietnam War; he participated in demonstrations with Native American activist organizations; and he taught his first language (Cherokee) to students in Oklahoma. During his acting career, Studi has received numerous awards—most recently a lifetime achievement award from the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences in 2019 (the only Native American to receive this honorary award). All applicants (except below-mentioned categories) residing in the USA and having valid Passport and Valid Visa Status (i.e., “Visa Page/EAD/Green Card/I-797A Approval Notice) are eligible to apply for re-issue of Passport under Tatkal Passport Scheme Below the list of Category of applicants are not eligible to apply under Tatkal Passport Scheme: Lost/ Stolen Passport/ Damaged beyond recognition Renewal of Short Validity Passport (SVP) Change in Name Change in Sex Change of Appearance (Minors can apply) Change/ Correction of Date of birth Change/ Correction of Place of birth Change in Signature (Minors can apply) Change of Father/ Mother's name Link to start - https://visa.vfsglobal.com/usa/en/ind You need to choose what service you are requesting. Passport has various types of options You can get more details , this link has step by step guide - https://visa.vfsglobal.com/usa/en/ind/apply-passport You can see the possible services and its check list here - https://visa.vfsglobal.com/one-pager/india/united-states-of-america/passport-services/ For My Case to Apply in Tatkal below is the required documents - The checklist for the application category that you apply for will provide details on which specific forms you may need to download. In some instances, there may be more than one form. Don’t forget to review Photograph Specification Complete a separate checklist and application form/s for each person applying. Ensure the documents are complete in all aspects and forms are duly where needed. • Tatkal Passport Scheme - Checklist • Sample Passport Online Application form • Annexure – E – Mandatory • Affidavit for change of Appearance and Signature - Mandatory • Sworn Affidavit for Indian Address YOU NEED TO FILL ALL FORMS , FOR EXAMPLE even if you are selecting no change in appearance in the Govt form , You still have to send the affidavit for change of appearance . ONCE you go through all this links - Follow below steps in the step by step guide - https://visa.vfsglobal.com/usa/en/ind/apply-passport To summarize these are key steps 1. Apply on Govt website . Note the application reference id . This will be the Govt reference id. 2. Create a profile on VFS and fill in details exactly matching with govt application and make the payment. 3. Print all documents and get it notarized ( I got it done from UPS) 4. Fill in all docs ( I did some of them by hand ) and prepare the checklist 5. I bought the shipping label with VFS , its recommended to track better. 6. Package everything in sequence with a check list of your own and send it . Dont forget to sign wherever required. Edit: I just received my passport today. Use below email addresses for escalation if facing delays. passport.sf@mea.gov.in customercare@vfsglobal.com cg.sf@mea.gov.in cca.cgisf@mea.gov.in dcg.sf@mea.gov.in info.ihcusa@vfshelpline.com Disclaimer - This is the process i followed and my passport was processed by embassy of SFO . Although there were some delays in shipping it back but application was accepted and processed by embassy. The U.S. Calvary didn’t understand and deemed the ghost dance a threat. Each year, Horse riders ride from Standing Rock and Cheyenne River Sioux Tribes to the Pine Ridge Reservation to honor and recognize our ancestors who lost their lives at Wounded Knee.  Wopila Tanka Big Thank You!\n\nBy 1890, pretty much all 100 million American Indians were either killed or sent to live on a reservation, by law.  The main source of food (buffalo) was decimated from 30-60 million to down to less than 1,000 by 1890.  So our ancestors danced and prayed in desperation, which many call the ghost dance.  The U.S. Calvary didn’t understand and deemed the ghost dance a threat.  This led to the U.S. Calvary killing our ancestors at Wounded Knee.\n\n*Today, December 29, we mourn and carry on the legacy of our ancestors*\n\nPlease share and teach others, so we do not repeat our past.  Instead, we must teach each other, especially our youth, so we can promote better understanding and respect for each other.  It’s time to dismantle racist misunderstandings, and promote education and unity.\n\nHecetuwedo, Mitakuye Today is a day of mourning of our 38+2 Dakota Grandfathers, who were executed by hanging the day after Christmas, December 26, 1862, Mankato, Minnesota, 158 years ago.  \n\nOur Dakota ancestors lived a good life in Minnesota (Mni Sota) for centuries.  Then when the settlers moved west the land was taken from them.  This led to conflict and all the same soldiers who fought our ancestors, were appointed to the military commission, who were biased and sentenced 303 of our ancestors to death.  Our ancestors didn’t understand English nor did they have legal counsel representing them, they had no idea what crimes they were being tried in court for.  This was completely lopsided and led to one-sided accounts and the hatred led to continuous pressure on President Lincoln to punish our ancestors\n\nPresident Abraham Lincoln eventually lowered the execution down to 38.  The Dakota 38+2 execution was the largest mass execution in our country’s history.  Throughout America, over 99 million out of 100 million of our ancestors died during westward expansion.  \n\nPray for our ancestors, live for our ancestors, heal for our ancestors.  Educate others about this history, so we will never repeat it and we hope our children will all disable racism and create a better future.  We do better, when we know better.\n\n~Always Remember the Dakota 38+2, and blessings to the horse back riders, runners and those who walk for awareness in Remembrance every year.  Hecetuwedo, Mitakuye 18:54:21","updated":"2022-01-06 20:08:38","type":"photo","message":"[Vegan Meal Announcement, 31 December] Hey everyone! This will be the last meal of the year! I want to prefix my meal announcement by saying thank you to you all. 2020 threw me some curves, but your support and cheery faces helped me to get through. I appreciate the opportunity to feed you and hope you'll come visit Truffles the porch kitty and I many more times. May there be more dal, more paneer, and more mirch masala (spices made with green chillies) in the New Year for all of us! Vegetable Kohlapuri with Punjabi Chole, Rice, and Vegan Naan Vegetable Kohlapuri is another favourite that we would get from a local restaurant back home in Delhi. While we kids were stuffing our faces with Malai kofta my dad would enjoy a plate of Vegetable Kolhapuri. It was enough of a treat for him that he was willing to take us noisy kids out and work to reign us in. Vegetable Kohlapuri is a spicy curry with mixed vegetables (potatoes, carrots, capsicum (bell pepper to you all), beans, and peas). The dish derives its name from the city of Kohlapur which is found in the district of Kohlapur on the Western Coast of India. The gravy gets it spiciness from dried red chillies and it's flavour from coconut, poppy seeds, and sesame seeds. Punjabi Choley a.k.a (a.k.a. chana masala) is Delhi‘s one of the most popular street foods. It is a curry made with white chickpeas, garlic, ginger, tomatoes, and tamarind to liven up the chickpeas ￼ This used to be one of the weekend dishes at home as it takes longer to cook and Mata-Rani (my mother) liked to spend time to get it right. She kept and used her own homemade Chana masala spices for this recipe which is a mix of cardamom, cloves, cumin seeds, fennel seeds, and dry pomegranate seeds. This Choley, in her opinion, is too good to leave in the hands of store-bought curry powders. The price of each plate is $15 and I accept Zelle. I'm selling the naan as an add-on at $3 for two pieces. Achari Paneer is a spicy Paneer curry with rich yogurt and tomato based sauce. The achari (Indian pickling mix of spices - Fennel, Nigella seeds, Fenugreek Seeds, and Mustard seeds) gives the sauce a flavour that defies description. It's a traditional North Indian recipe and another one of the recipes I learnt to cook after leaving home and one of the few dishes I was able to teach mata-rani (my mother). This dish will be served with a healthy portion of Daal palak. Daal Palak is Mata-rani’s favourite type of lentils, she loves them with basmati rice. My mother used to cook this when Papa (my dad) would travel for work. For some reason, she would make Daal Palak with jackfruit. Please don't worry, that is a combination I will spare you. We kids never got the hang of eating jackfruit. My mother’s recipe for Daal Palak (aside from the aforementioned) involves equal parts Arhar Dal (Split pigeon peas) and Masoor dal (red lentils) tempered in ghee with cumin, dried red chilles, green chillies, garlic, and onions. She and I both serve them with basmati rice and some sabzi or other. (Sabzi सब्ज़ी is the Hindi word for curry.) The idea is to mix it all up and enjoy! The price of each plate is $15 and I accept Zelle. I'm selling the naan as an add-on at $3 for two pieces.
